<font color="#FF0000">BETRAYAL</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov 17  5:56:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Paul,<br>
   Your thoughts on abandonment and betrayal really struck a chord with me.  I got to thinking about my own experience with betrayal and the devastation is caused in my life.  I was betrayed by the person I had bestowed all of my trust in, my husband of fourteen years.  It nearly killed me.  I was shocked by the tremendous anger and rage I felt.  It brought forth every raw emotion imaginable and I remember looking in the mirror and thinking how I looked like a ten year old child - like one who had just lost her mother (abandonment). <br><br>
But as I said before, our greatest gifts sometimes come in the strangest packages.  When the pain became absolutely unbearable, I remember collapsing in a heap on the floor, nowhere to turn, giving up or giving into it.  It was at that moment I experienced my most profound spiritual experience of my life.  I was suddenly wrapped up in this incredible warm white light and I will never forget nor be able to properly convey the powerful peace and forgiveness that overcame my entire being.  I have no doubt that I had angels on hand that had waited a long time for me to turn off my thoughts and will for one second so that the door could open to allow them in. One moment I was ready to kill or die and the next I was comforting my husband who was sobbing on the bed (I was completely at peace).  We lasted another 6 years, but split up amicably nearly 3 years ago.<br><br>
Those few seconds of &quot;grace&quot; profoundly altered my life forever.  I believe the key was &quot;letting go&quot;, &quot;turning it over&quot;, not trying, but &quot;allowing&quot;.  I had no idea of what forgiveness really meant until then nor had I really ever turned over my will.  Understanding forgiveness on that unconditional level eventually led me to forgive myself for all of my imperfections and hence forgiving and being more tolerant of others.  That then led me to start nurturing and trusting myself and then willingly trusting others (flaws and all).  <br><br>
Bottom line...I'm far more trusting now than I was before the betrayal.  When I gave myself less emotionally and spiritually, the trust I bestowed on someone felt like a life or death matter - it set up a situation where I was essentially worshiping the wrong God. <br><br>
 Now, when I trust someone, I'm not blackmailing them with my trust.  I am able to love more purely because it is safer to open my heart wider because it is less conditional, I'm not &quot;looking&quot; for the other person to let me down, I'm not relying on them to be the sole supplier of my emotional worth.  It's far more satisfying to savor what they do give me than coming from a place of need which requires me to focus on what they're NOT giving me...abundance vs. limitation...gratitude vs. expectation. <br><br>
 Sometimes people say &quot;I don't need anyone&quot; with an &quot;edge&quot;, but to do it with the heart wide open takes a great deal of faith.  If I find my heart shutting down in the &quot;protection mode&quot; I now know to look to myself and God, rather than to my partner for a &quot;fix&quot;.  Sometimes it's difficult...the ego can sometimes be a very wayward computer, but the road is the right one, I'm sure.  I'm sorry if this is rambling, but these thoughts have been coming together all day and I haven't really got them organized yet. <br><br>
Anyway, I guess the moral of the story is...The more we &quot;need&quot; to trust, the more we find we can't.  Letting go of the &quot;need&quot; to trust helps us to let go of the impossible requirements we put on others and our need to police their behavior. Then it is easier to forgive which is a gift to ourselves, making it easier to trust ourselves and hence trusting others without the &quot;need&quot;.  It's this complete cycle.  <br><br>
Nearly all religions teach us to &quot;let go&quot; of our will and turn all things over to God/the universe/spirit.  When we trust that, all else falls in place.  It's scarey as hell at first, but I found it wasn't just an &quot;interesting philosophy.&quot;  It's a far more fulfilling reality.<br><br>
So maybe the Vietnam Vet's extreme experience with trust, betrayal and abandonment is really a gift in disguise.  If you can't do it the old way you're forced to forge ahead to little known territory - enlightenment.  Though it's possible to get there an easier way, most of us won't jump unless we're pushed...&quot;Blessed are the poor in spirit for their's is the kingdom of heaven.&quot;<br><br>
Man, I can babble on...<br><br>
ANNE
